single_game_results.explain: With this game, the setup is simple, the gameplay is challenging yet rewarding, and the scoring is complex. To play, I have to throw dodgeballs into the bin, then stack cube blocks onto the bridge block. The setup includes a flat block placed on the rug as to not move as I gain points to build structures in gameplay with the flat block and a cube block to earn 10 points for each object used. Also, three pyramid blocks are arranged on the floor with one hexagonal bin in a square format as I play and score by throwing dodgeballs into the hexagonal bin while standing next to each pyramid. I like the idea of having to move around so the notion of throwing the ball then having to rush to make contact with it after it hits a wall can be the side effect of a little workout. single_game_results.overall: Might be a bit repetitive, might become bored with it fast. I feel like it is not too creative.

single_game_results.overall: It is a fairly simple game, but could definitely provide some entertainment for a while. I think the skill needed for the game is pretty basic and the learning curve would not be too steep. It would likely become boring after a while.
single_game_results.explain: In this game you set up by placing a hexagonal bin upright at the base of a triangular ramp. Then, you throw a ball at the ramp so that it will slide into the hexagonal bin. You get a point for each time the ball slides into the bin. The game ends when the hexagonal bin can no longer stand up without assistance.

This game involves setting up by placing a hexagonal bin near the rug, where it will stay for the duration of the game. Then, you throw various balls including golf balls, basketballs, and dodgeballs at specific objects. You get a point if your golf ball lands on a hexagonal bin. You get 40 points when you have either a basketball or white golf ball on top of the top drawer, a basketball on a hexagonal bin, and a dodgeball on a hexagonal bin at the same time.
single_game_results.overall: This game seems a little complicated to grasp. It is difficult to know how to get all the different balls in the spots you want simultaneously. It seems a little weird, and I don't think I would enjoy it very much.

I struggle to understand the point of the game. Firstly, the set up seems to be disjointed from the actual gameplay. Secondly, I do not know what is meant by "type of block". Is the type the shape, or the color, or both? There is also no defined end to the game despite scoring happening at the end.
single_game_results.explain: Set up this game by placing all green bridge blocks on the rug and make sure they stay there for the duration of the game. To play the game you must stack a cube block and a flat block on top of another block of the same type as the cube block. You get six points for each stack meeting this criteria when the game ends.

single_game_results.overall: This seems like a pretty fun game to play. The directions are clear and I feel like I understand what I need to do. I would prefer to have a defined end of the game.
single_game_results.explain: To set up for playing this game, a hexagonal bin must be placed and remain near the rug for the duration of the game. You must throw dodgeballs at either the doggie bed or the hexagonal bin trying to land on them. You earn points for each dodgeball resting on the doggie bed or the hexagonal bin. Your final score is found by adding these points together.

single_game_results.overall: The game is a bit convoluted but appears to be pretty interesting. The game play is a bit difficult to understand but the scoring system makes it make more sense. The game has enough layers to be engaging without being too difficult to achieve.
single_game_results.explain: To play this game, set up by placing all golf balls, dodgeballs, triangle blocks, and pyramid blocks near a side table making sure no chair is directly in front of the desk for the duration of the game. A curved wooden ramp should be placed so that the front is adjacent to the front of the desk and a hexagonal bin should be placed facing the back of the ramp. All objects placed should remain where they are the whole game. Start the game by standing next to the bed and throwing golf balls, dodgeballs, triangle blocks, and pyramid blocks at the hexagonal bin, or so they touch a desktop or laptop computer. Golf balls have an additional condition of having to touch the ramp before landing in the hexagonal bin. Point values are as follows: Triangle Block - 1pt, Pyramid Block - 2pts, Dodgeball - 2pts, Golf Ball - 3pts. Points come from landing in the hexagonal bin. An additional 6 pts may be earned by touching the golf ball to the ramp before landing in the bin. For each object that touches a computer, a point is lost.

To play this game, place a hexagonal bin near the door where it will remain during gameplay. Throw golf balls and dodgeballs at the bin, trying to land on top of or inside the bin. Successful throws are those in which golf balls stop on top of the bin or dodgeballs land inside or on top of the bin. The final score is the addition of these points.
single_game_results.overall: This game is a fairly simple concept but the scoring system makes it interesting. I like that the different balls have different objectives. It looks like it would be fairly difficult to master which makes it challenging and fun.

single_game_results.explain: Set up to play by sourcing a chair, a hexagonal bin, a teddy bear and a ramp and placing them in the room with the teddy bear on the chair, the triangular ramp at the center of the room with the chair in front of it, and the hexagonal bin and a ball placed together on the other side of the chair. To play, pick up the teddy bear and throw it towards the hexagonal bin and ball. Five points are earned if the teddy bear lands in the hexagonal bin and one point if it touches the ball.
single_game_results.overall: There is no point in having the ramp in the game really, but otherwise it seems pretty simple. The idea of throwing a teddy bear that is sitting in a chair is pretty cute and funny but the game seems pretty short.

single_game_results.explain: Set up by placing a hexagonal bin on the rug, where it will stay for the entire game. To play, throw dodgeballs at the hexagonal bin or the doggie bed. Points are earned for dodgeballs that land inside the bin or on the doggie bed. Final score is the addition of these points.
single_game_results.overall: This is a simple game to get to understand and seems like it would be pretty fun to try to do. I think it is easy to understand but would take at least some skill to execute properly.

single_game_results.explain: To set up for this game, place a hexagonal bin near the door where it will stay for the entire game. To play the game, move various objects in the room to specific locations including the top shelf, near the floor, and near the north wall ensuring the objects are stationary. Also hold and throw dodgeballs at the hexagonal bin so that they stop and land on the top of the bin. Points are earned for each object in the specific places and each dodgeball on top of the bin. Find the final score by adding these points together.
single_game_results.overall: This games seems pretty fun and interesting! I like the idea of placing objects in different areas. I think the game would be more fun if it specified which objects should go where beyond the dodgeballs in the bin.

single_game_results.explain: To play this game, place objects near the rug and make sure they are stationary. After three minutes, a point is earned for each stationary object near the rug.
single_game_results.overall: I like the simplicity of the goal of this game. I can imagine laughing and playing with the objects trying to get them to stay on the rug and not move. I like that the game has a determined end point.

debrief_responses.strategy: I didn't really have a strategy, I just read the description and went with how I felt about the game.

debrief_responses.comments: I used the text entry box to type out certain notes as I worked the idea through my mind, but those details were either incorporated into the response or deleted prior to submitting. In my head, I sometimes feel that an equation is better at describing a situation than literal words. And so it was not clear from the instructions whether an algebraic equation could fit the definition of a word. Also, in the design, it was not clear whether there was a door in the corner that was not visible in the images. I felt it was possible the two glass panes would be a doorway to the bedroom, but it seemed far more likely the door was in the unknown corner. Several game prompts made reference to a door and it was not clear from the visible environment where that was located. This was important when the instructions called for the hexbin to be placed near the door, and an advantage could be gained by positioning the bin relative to the room corner. But the corner would not be a valid item unless there was also a door near the corner.
debrief_responses.techDifficulties: Not that I am aware of. Everything seemed to run smoothly. I was quite confident that I submitted the same response answers on my second attempt on the quiz as I did on the first, but I am not more than 75% confident in this. I am almost entirely that a majority of my answers were the same, but I was navigating with my keyboard and it is possible a response was inadvertently switched. I say this only because I feel there is a small chance the quiz might be defective and incorrectly requires a second attempt.
debrief_responses.strategy:
This is easiest on a point-by-point basis. For the re-explaining, I tried not to fill in the gaps with assumptions, but I felt that there were certain instances where an assumption was necessary to understand the game and therefore a leap of faith was a necessity. An example of this would be in matching the block types between cubes and rectangles. The type was a core requirement of the point system and therefore essential to the game execution. I felt that it was impossible to imagine obtaining points without creating an understanding of what was meant by the block type. But for the most part, I tried to break the descriptions down to explicitly define how points are awarded and the conditions that certain points can be modified through a bonus outcome. If there were limitations, I tried to describe those separately from the points, unless the limitations were unique only to one point method, and then I tried to tie the limitations directly into my point awarding explanation. 

For human-like/machine-like, I considered whether the task seemed like it could be a reasonable product of imagination. Or a simple enough instruction set that it could keep young children occupied for a short while. I had a more difficult time with the games that seemed more extreme. For example, gaining one point for each item on top of the bed. In this, I could see a competitive side from the tetris perspective. It also seemed quite risk in a realisticly virtual setting in that the room contained computer equipment, though I understand this was not a game object, but it was difficult to put out of mind. I felt that the item I most needed in this setup, was the Terminal details, but these were not given. I feel that if a reasonably difficult time limit was set, then it would be human-like. But if the event was open, then the outcome would be one such that a maximum score would be too easily achieved. Requiring only the effort to relocate all moveable items. In summary, I felt that it was more machine like when the outcome was less competitive in a relocation action, or when the mental demand far exceeded the physical demand (such as in the logic block stacking level).

The more mentally complicated tasks would be more enjoyable to observe because I feel it would allow for an opportunity to observation to better understand the other player. With the more physical competitions, it is less interesting and more of a matter of patience.

An inaccurate throw may knock a ball off the shelf and into the hexbin, this must be avoided. The pencils must leave the drawer, but must not make it into the hexbin. The user is free to relocate them elsewhere. All CC,CD and pencils left in the drawer will count negatively towards the user score. All CC and CD that are out of the top drawer, but not in the hexbin will count negatively towards the user score. This equation will determine the final score: (CC+CD)-3(sum($#balls_in_bin + $#CC_not_in_bin_but_not_in_drawer + $#CD_not_in_bin_but_not_in_drawer + $#CC_leftover_top + $#CD_leftover_top + $#pencil_leftover_top)).

single_game_results.explain: The user is granted 1 point value for each iteration. One iteration involves retrieving a ball from the shelf, launching it towards a bedroom wall, and retrieving the ball prior to the ball hitting any surface. The user is granted one point and may repeat the process if the ball is caught and possession is maintained. If the user makes contact with the ball, but fails to maintain possession, the user is awarded one point, but the ball is no longer in play. single_game_results.overall: The game play instructions remind me of a game I played as a kid called wallball. Pretty generic, but also very effective for capturing the focus and attention of a player.

single_game_results.explain: The user must place the hexbin in the corner of the room that is not shown in the images above, where there must be a bedroom door. The bin must be rotated such that the shorter side is facing the wall and the tall side is facing the user. The user may select the specific location of the hexbin such that it is close enough to satisfy as being considered near the door. The user must identify an ideal placement such that the circumference of the topside of the hexbin is placed at a distanced from the wall so that it is possible to for a ball to land and remain wedged in place, without falling either into the hexbin or off the edge. single_game_results.overall: This game sounds like it is the result of many hours spent developing a simple boredom killing game into a feat of masterful precision. I imagine the final result would be something of a house of cards, except made from 6 balls. I have a lot of respect for this game design if, in fact, I have imagined it correctly.

single_game_results.overall: Dull, boring, computer generated without any sense of human entertainment taken into consideration. Not very fun at all.
single_game_results.explain: There is a bin near the room center which you have to pick up and place objects into the bin, or set them in motion by rolling or tossing them into the bin. Each object into the bin earns a single point.

single_game_results.overall: Boring. This is not a game, sort of a time passer people do when bored. It seems AI generated, without human touch.

Points based on the rug color where the ball stops. 1 for pink 2 for yellow 3 for orange 3 for green 4 for purple.

single_game_results.overall: This is another near impossible game to do. The AI does not understand the physics it seems or nuances of instructions, and games whether or not they are even probable in some cases possible. Nonsense, boring game. Not interested.

single_game_results.overall: This game is somewhat confusing to me but I think that it has the potential to be a good game.
single_game_results.explain: Essentially, there is a hexagonal bin in the game and you have to make sure that you place it near the rug and make sure that it stays there for the entire game. For the game play, you will be moving chairs on to desks and placing teddy bears on them, making sure that you are not positioning it diagonally. You will be scored based on how many chairs and teddy bears that are not positioned diagonally at the end of the game. Each chair on a desk will be worth 80 points and each teddy bear will be worth 1 point.

In this game, you stack blocks in certain ways and throw red dodgeballs. You earn points by making stacks of the balls. The point system consist of different combinations and each combination is worth certain points. Each time you throw a red dodgeball and it stops, you get a point.
single_game_results.overall: This game is far too confusing and I hate it.

single_game_results.explain: In this game you just throw dodgeballs and hope they land in the bin. If the dodgeball stops moving inside the bin, you get a point.
single_game_results.overall: I think I played this type of game before and it is a decent game.

single_game_results.explain: In this game you just throw dodgeballs in a hexagonal bin. For each dodgeball that you throw in the bin and stops moving, you get 1 point.
single_game_results.overall: I think that this game is simple. I played this type of game before so it was easy to understand. Overall, it is a decent game.
This game is very understandable and simple. It could be very fun to play.
single_game_results.explain: In this game, you have to throw dodgeballs to the top of the shelf. The balls have to stay still on the top shelf. You have 30 seconds to throw balls. You will earn a point for each dodgeball that is still on the top shelf at the end of the game.

In this game, there will be a hexagonal bin under the rug that will remain there for the entire game. To play the game, you have to throw a dodgeball so that it touches the top shelf and have to land and rest on the hexagonal bin. You will earn a point if the ball you threw touches the top shelf and ends up on the hexagonal bin.
single_game_results.overall: This game seems to be a good game but I think you can get bored from it after playing for a while. Overall it is not really creative because I think that anyone can come up with it.
I do not like this game. I think that I would get pretty frustrated playing this game.
single_game_results.explain: In this game, there will be a dodgeball near the desk. You have to throw the dodgeball so that it touches the south wall while it is still moving and you have to make sure that the dodgeball or teddy bear is not in your hand when it's in motion. The game will last for 60 seconds. You will earn a point every time you successfully throw the dodgeball and it touches the south wall and stops moving.

single_game_results.overall: I think that this game is interesting and well thought out. It should be fun to play.

debrief_responses.strategy: I read the descriptions of the games and thought about how it would look like if I am playing it. Then, I jot it down based on the steps that I had in mind. I used the original description and paraphrased it a bit when I had difficulty of understanding on how the game should be played.

single_game_results.explain: The objective of the game is to throw dodgeballs while avoiding throwing any dodgeballs inside of the doggie bed. For every dodgeball that is thrown that successfully avoid the doggie bed, the player will get 1 point, however every dodgeball that lands inside of the doggie bed loses the player 3 points.
single_game_results.overall: The game seems very uninteresting and almost dumb, there are no rules about what direction the ball can be thrown, how the ball must be thrown, and with a small doggie bed being the only target to avoid, it would seem like the simplest way to win the game would be to just lightly toss the ball in the opposite direction to the doggie bed. On top of this, there is no terminal to the game, so the player would just continue throwing balls for no reason until they get bored (which would probably be quick).

This game just seems like any of the million games that exist to put a ball inside of a goal. The rules don't specify what distance the player must be from the bin so I'd imagine I could just stand right above the bin and toss them directly in. Also, the numbers of 6 makes in 15 attempts seem pretty arbitrary.
single_game_results.explain: The objective of this game is to toss balls into a hexagonal bin. You get 15 attempts to throw the ball inside of the bin, and win if you score 6 or more points.

single_game_results.overall: This game seems pretty ridiculous. The point of the game is to throw a ball, and you get points when the ball stops. One would assume that all balls that are thrown eventually stop, so the object of the game isn't even to make sure the balls stop moving, it is to simply throw a ball. I don't see any redeeming or appealing qualities about this game, other than potentially finding the act of throwing a ball fun.
single_game_results.explain: To play this game, you need to place a dodgeball near a desk, then pick up the dodgeball and throw it. Points are scored anytime the dodgeball is thrown and then comes to a stop.

single_game_results.overall: This game doesn't seem very fun. Your objective is to roll a ball near a bin. That's it. I guess it could be interesting to see if you can roll the ball in different ways, or try to get the ball on a certain side of the bin, but as it stands, the game seems very boring.
single_game_results.explain: This game seems similar to bowling or golf, in that the objective is to roll a ball and have it land on a hexagonal bin. Once a ball is thrown, the player earns 1 point, however if the dodgeball lands or stops on the bin, the player earns an additional 5 points.

The goal of the game is to throw three different types of balls onto specific targets. Each time a golfball is thrown on a hexagonal bin, the player gets 1 point, each time a basketball is thrown on top of the top drawer, the player gets 40 points, and each time a player simultaneously throws a white golfball on top of the top drawer, a basketball on the hexagonal bin and a dodgeball on a hexagonal bin, the player scores 40 points.
single_game_results.overall: The game seems very complicated, with various ways of scoring points, however the difference in points for throwing a golfball on the bin as opposed to the other targets that award 40 points seems like a very simple strategy would quickly be made to achieve the easiest shot for the most amount of points.

This just seems like a baby game to get them to clean up their toys, just place every object you see inside of the bin and hope most of them are unique. Maybe the game could be improved if the player is penalized for every duplicate object that is put into the bin.
single_game_results.explain: After placing a hexagonal bin in the center of the room, the player must move different objects into the bin, and earn 1 point for each unique object that is successfully placed in the bin.

single_game_results.overall: I guess the game seems interesting, you want to roll the ball over the ramp at a certain speed or strength so that it lands on the bed and doesn't overshoot, however I'm confused about the ball stopping and touching the player, is the ball gravitated towards the player so that it always comes back and touches them if they miss the bed?
single_game_results.explain: After positioning a curved ramp near the center of the room facing the bed, the objective is to roll the ball over the ramp and then land on the bed in order to earn points, however if the ball doesn't land on the bed and instead comes to a stop and touches the player, the player loses points. The final score is determined by subtracting the number of times the dodgeball successfully landed on the bed by the number of times the ball missed the bed and touched the player

single_game_results.overall: The game doesn't make too much sense, and maybe the description is just throwing me off, but what's the point of the green bridge blocks? And what is considered the same "type" of block? It seems like the objective of the game is to just stack blocks on top of one another, seems pretty uninteresting.
single_game_results.explain: The objective of the game is to stack different types of blocks, earning 6 points for each stack at the end of the game. The player must stack a cube shaped block and a flat block on top of a black that is the same type as the cube block.

single_game_results.overall: So the game is like two different games, each with their own scoring systems. Stacking chairs on tables seems like it would be a waste of time considering you only get 1 point, while it might obstruct the vision or movement of the ball, which gains 40 points when it lands on the bin. Seems like the game should just be throwing a basketball in the bin, no chairs involved.
single_game_results.explain: After placing a hexagonal bin near the rug and stacking the chairs on the desks, the player must throw basketball so that they land on top of the hexagonal bin. The player earns 1 point for every chair that is stacked on a desk, and 40 points for every basketball that lands on top of the bin.

single_game_results.overall: This game seems pretty boring and simple. Just throw a dodgeball on top of the bin. My overall impression here is pretty negative simply because it seems so mundane.
single_game_results.explain: This game is very simple, throw a dodgeball on top of a hexagonal bin. The player earns 1 point for each dodgeball that successfully lands on top of the bin.
